        "line": 94,
        "path": "Paper/4_Evaluation.tex",
        "text": "The app-level result uses SQLite transaction latency because it exercises the mounted file-encryption path, foreground tail latency, and elastic background pressure together.  Table~\\ref{tab:qos_sqlite_recovery} reports five-run hero medians and three-run kernel QoS controls.  AEGIS-Q reports 8.15~ms p99, zero median misses, and 3.02~MB/s background progress; unthrottled storage reports 9.62~ms and 6.98~MB/s.  This is a Pareto point rather than a free throughput improvement: the simple controller reaches 7.54~ms p99 but only 1.50~MB/s background progress.  Kernel controls preserve background throughput but not the tail here: \\texttt{ionice} reports 16.22~ms p99 with six misses, and \\texttt{IOWeight} reports 12.57~ms p99 with seven misses.  This is bounded storage-visible control, not a uniqueness or non-storage QoS claim."
      },
      {
        "guarded": true,
        "line": 96,
        "path": "Paper/4_Evaluation.tex",
        "text": "The sensitivity bundle varies budget, sampling interval, threshold, queue depth, and writer intensity.  The default storage-pressure controller uses 20~ms telemetry sampling, 0.70/0.60 enter/exit thresholds, and a two-sample hold; admission defaults are 4~KiB minimum GPU batches, 1.73~ms minimum producer slack, 100~\\(\\mu\\)s deadline margin, 250~ms slack freshness, and 0.80 queue threshold.  Baseline p99 is 6.4~ms; 80~ms sampling and 128~KiB chunks remain at 7.0/7.2~ms, high threshold disables throttling (0 sleeps, 8.8~ms), and two writers is fragile (12.3~ms, one miss).  No-throttle/no-slack fallbacks pass, and hysteresis records 9 transitions and 8 flips.  This keeps the claim on mounted storage-visible control, not an external application scheduler."
      }
